   <abstract>Alice Joyce was born on October 1, 1890 in Kansas City, Missouri. She worked as a telephone operator and as a fashion model before entering film in 1910. She went on earn the nickname "The Madonna of the Screen" and to make a number of silent films, including "Whom the Gods Destroy" (1916), "Within the Law" (1917), "Stella Dallas" (1925), and "So's Your Old Man" (1926). Joyce retired in 1930 with the advent of "talkies." She was married three times: first to Tom Moore (from 1914 to 1920), second to James Regan (from 1920 to 1932), and finally to Clarence Brown (from 1933 to 1945). Alice Joyce Brown died of heart disease on October 9, 1955 and was buried in the San Fernando Mission Cemetery.</abstract>
